        <h1>Dishwasher Door Spring Repair Cost in Los Angeles</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          Dishwasher door springs fail at 6-8 years of daily use on most mass-market brands — the symptom is
          the door falling open heavy when you unlatch it, or slamming shut when you release from partial
          position, or the door refusing to stay in intermediate positions during loading. Our LA service
          typical for door-spring replacement runs <b>$150–$280 parts + labor</b>, with variance driven by
          brand-specific spring design (tension-spring vs cable-and-pulley balance systems), whether the
          cable routing needs replacement alongside the springs, and whether the door-hinge mechanism needs
          realignment after spring swap. $89 residential diagnostic fee is waived when you authorize the
          repair.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-cta">
          <a href="tel:+14243250520" class="btn btn-primary">Call (424) 325-0520</a>
          <a href="#book" class="btn btn-ghost">Request a Visit</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="trust-bar">
    <div class="wrap">
      <span>BBB Accredited Business</span>
      <span>BHGS #A49573 · Insured</span>
      <span>Same-day in 5 SoCal counties</span>
      <span>Residential diagnostic $89 · waived with repair</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>What dishwasher door springs actually do</h2>
      <p>
        Your dishwasher's door is heavy — stainless-steel interior, stainless-tub back panel, door-gasket
        assembly, and often a panel-ready cabinetry panel on the exterior add up to 15-30 pounds on most
        built-in dishwashers. The door-spring system (either a pair of tension springs or a cable-and-pulley
        balance system depending on the brand platform) counterbalances this weight so the door opens
        gently from vertical to horizontal and stays at intermediate loading positions without falling open
        or slamming shut.
      </p>
      <p>
        When springs weaken or fail, three symptoms appear: (1) door falls open heavy when you release the
        latch — the counterbalance isn't holding anymore; (2) door slams shut forcefully when you release
        from partial-open position — again, spring tension inadequate to hold; (3) door refuses to stay at
        intermediate positions while loading, making rack access frustrating. Some brands fail one spring
        at a time (asymmetric door behavior — one side drops faster than the other), which is a clear
        diagnostic signal on tension-spring platforms.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>Typical LA door-spring repair cost bands by brand</h2>
      <table class="price-table">
        <tr><th>Brand platform</th><th>Typical range</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Bosch (BSH) — tension-spring</td><td>$165 – $245</td><td>800 Series, 500 Series, 300 Series, Ascenta</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Thermador (BSH) — tension-spring</td><td>$185 – $265</td><td>BSH sibling to Bosch; same platform</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Samsung — cable-and-pulley</td><td>$170 – $260</td><td>DW80 series most common</td></tr>
        <tr><td>LG — cable-and-pulley</td><td>$175 – $270</td><td>LDT, LDF series</td></tr>
        <tr><td>KitchenAid (Whirlpool) — tension-spring</td><td>$165 – $245</td><td>KDTE, KDTM, KDPE series</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Whirlpool — tension-spring</td><td>$150 – $230</td><td>WDT series</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Maytag (Whirlpool) — tension-spring</td><td>$155 – $235</td><td>MDB series</td></tr>
        <tr><td>GE — tension-spring</td><td>$160 – $240</td><td>GDF, GDT series</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Miele — specialty tension</td><td>$220 – $340</td><td>Miele-platform specific parts, 3-7 day lead</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Asko — specialty</td><td>$240 – $360</td><td>Asko-platform specific, 5-10 day lead</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Beko (Arçelik) — tension-spring</td><td>$170 – $260</td><td>18" compact and 24" standard</td></tr>
        <tr><td>SMEG — Italian-platform specific</td><td>$260 – $380</td><td>7-14 day Italian parts lead</td></tr>
        <tr><td>JennAir (Whirlpool) — tension-spring</td><td>$180 – $280</td><td>JDB, JDPSS series</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Frigidaire — tension-spring</td><td>$150 – $220</td><td>FGID, FFID, FFCD series</td></tr>
      </table>
      <p class="small">All ranges include $89 residential diagnostic (waived with repair) plus parts plus labor. Ranges assume single-visit completion on common-platform parts; Asko / Miele / SMEG specialty-parts ranges reflect longer lead times.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>Bosch / Samsung / LG — the three most-common LA door-spring calls</h2>

      <h3>Bosch door springs (BSH tension-spring system)</h3>
      <p>
        Bosch 800 Series, 500 Series, 300 Series, and Ascenta dishwashers all use a tension-spring pair
        counterbalance system on the door hinges. The springs hook into the lower cabinet frame and attach
        to the hinge-assembly bracket at the door. Failure is usually one spring at a time (asymmetric door
        behavior) at 6-8 years of daily use. Replacement is straightforward on-site: lay the unit on its
        back or side for hinge access, remove the worn springs, install new springs, verify door balance
        at multiple positions. Typical service $165–$245 including $89 diagnostic fee waived. Cable
        variants on some newer Bosch generations run slightly higher ($185–$265).
      </p>

      <h3>Samsung door springs (cable-and-pulley balance system)</h3>
      <p>
        Samsung dishwashers — DW80 series prominently — use a cable-and-pulley door-balance system rather
        than direct tension springs. The cables route from the door hinge through pulley guides to a spring
        mechanism inside the lower cabinet frame. Failure modes: (1) cable wear and fraying at 6-8 years;
        (2) spring mechanism failure (spring fatigue inside the cabinet assembly); (3) pulley-guide wear
        causing binding. Complete repair often requires both cable and spring replacement since failure of
        one accelerates wear on the other. Typical service $170–$260 for standard cable + spring service;
        $240–$320 if pulley-guide hardware also needs replacement.
      </p>

      <h3>LG door springs (cable-and-pulley similar to Samsung)</h3>
      <p>
        LG LDT and LDF dishwasher families use cable-and-pulley balance similar in concept to Samsung but
        with LG-specific hardware. Failure timeline and symptoms mirror Samsung: asymmetric door behavior
        or overall door-heavy feel at 6-8 years. Service $175–$270 standard, $250–$330 if pulley hardware
        also degraded. LG's broader service network has adequate parts availability on door-spring components
        across LA.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>Why door springs fail at 6-8 years in LA specifically</h2>
      <p>
        Door-spring wear is usage-cycle-driven rather than age-driven per se. LA households typically run
        dishwashers 1.5-2 cycles per day on average (higher in multi-member households), which translates
        to ~500-750 door-open-close cycles per year per spring. Spring fatigue at 4,000-6,000 cycles is the
        typical residential-service-life expectation, which maps to 6-8 years. Apartment and rental-property
        installs with higher turnover (Airbnb short-term rental applications, multifamily shared laundry-
        kitchen setups) see accelerated wear at 4-5 years.
      </p>
      <p>
        Secondary environmental factor: LA's hot summer kitchens can accelerate spring metal fatigue slightly
        through thermal cycling. Not a dominant factor but worth noting on 8-plus-year-old units — if
        another spring-system component is due for service, replace the full assembly to avoid return visits.
      </p>
      <p>
        Preventive note: many LA appliance-repair calls for "dishwasher door spring" are actually door-gasket
        compression loss creating perceived spring-resistance issues. Our techs verify the actual failure
        mode (spring vs gasket vs hinge) before quoting — sometimes the cheaper fix ($220–$340 gasket swap)
        resolves what sounded like a spring problem.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>What's included in our $150-$280 door-spring service</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>$89 residential diagnostic fee (waived when you authorize the repair)</li>
        <li>Door-spring part replacement (tension springs, cable + pulley assembly, or specialty-platform equivalent)</li>
        <li>Door-balance verification at multiple positions (closed, 30°, 60°, 90° open)</li>
        <li>Hinge-assembly inspection + re-alignment if misalignment detected post-spring swap</li>
        <li>Door-gasket inspection during spring service (catches disguised-gasket-fault cases before return visit)</li>
        <li>90-day warranty on labor and installed parts</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Ranges above exclude cabinet removal (required on some integrated built-in platforms at $80-$160
